post_cb({"27699714": {"ViewCount": "60", "Body": "<p>As known, static data members shall not be defined in the class definition: </p>\n<p><code>N4296:9.4.2/2 [class.static.data]</code></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27699714_27699714_0\">The declaration of a static data member in its class definition is not\n  a definition and may be of an incomplete type other than cv-qualified\n  void. The definition for a static data member shall appear in a\n  namespace scope enclosing the member\u2019s class definition.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Consider the following class:</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nstruct A\n{\n    enum E { x = 2, y = 3 }; //both enuerators are defined in the definition of `A`\n};\n\nint x = A::x; //looks like A::x is static data member, despite being defined in the scope of `A`\n\nint main(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; x &lt;&lt; std::endl; }\n</code></pre>\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://coliru.stacked-crooked.com/a/272832a1c4f5788e\" rel=\"nofollow\">DEMO</a></strong></p>\n<p>In the example all the enumerators were declared within the class scope, actually: </p>\n<p><code>N4296::7.2/11 [dcl.enum]</code></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27699714_27699714_1\">Each enum-name and each unscoped enumerator is declared in the scope\n  that immediately contains the enum-specifier.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So, it's not clear unscoped enumerators are static or non-static data members. We can use them outside of an <code>object-expression</code>, therefore they should be static. On the other hand, we can't define static data members in a class scope. It looks a bit contradictory to me, couldn't you clarify that?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "27702619", "Title": "Unscoped enumerators within a class definition", "CreationDate": "2014-12-30T04:50:14.193", "Id": "27699714", "CommentCount": "4", "LastEditDate": "2015-06-07T01:27:00.463", "PostTypeId": "1", "OwnerDisplayName": "user2953119", "LastEditorUserId": "64046", "LastActivityDate": "2015-06-07T01:27:00.463", "Score": "0", "Tags": "<c++><class><enums><nested>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "27702619": {"Id": "27702619", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>[class.mem]/p1:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27699714_27702619_0\">Members of a class are data members, member functions (9.3), nested\n  types, and enumerators.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Enumerators are not data members.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-12-30T09:19:43.150", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-12-30T09:19:43.150", "ParentId": "27699714", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2756719"}, "27700121": {"Id": "27700121", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>In your example, <code>A::x</code> is not a data member at all.  It has no storage.  To prove this to yourself, try taking its address: you can't.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-12-30T05:38:13.157", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2014-12-30T05:38:13.157", "ParentId": "27699714", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "4323"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_27699714_27702619_0": {"length": 9, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5861}, "so_27699714_27699714_1": {"length": 10, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5470}, "so_27699714_27699714_0": {"length": 26, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 5907}}, "n3337": {"so_27699714_27702619_0": {"length": 9, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5631}, "so_27699714_27699714_1": {"length": 10, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5256}, "so_27699714_27699714_0": {"length": 26, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 5679}}, "n4659": {"so_27699714_27702619_0": {"length": 9, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 7340}, "so_27699714_27699714_1": {"length": 10, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6904}, "so_27699714_27699714_0": {"length": 24, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "section_id": 7389}}}});